<subSubSection id="E7A2B298FFD4786B6FBE1F6FFB3D7D06" box="[199,1268,1110,1135]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="AF07E113FFD4786B6FBE1F6FFB3D7D06" blockId="33.[151,1436,390,1206]" box="[199,1268,1110,1135]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="9DCC3D01FFD4786B6FBE1F6FFE847D07" bold="true" box="[199,333,1111,1135]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is descriptive for the subapical group of spines on the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E7A2B298FFD4786B6FBE1F43FE2A7DDE" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="AF07E113FFD4786B6FBE1F43FE2A7DDE" blockId="33.[151,1436,390,1206]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="9DCC3D01FFD4786B6FBE1F43FEF27DFB" bold="true" box="[199,315,1147,1171]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species has a unique aedeagal, subapical lateral lobe adorned with setae which will separate it from all other known species.
</paragraph>
